<p>&#8220;I know that people are reluctant to voice objections to things I’ve said, not because I’ve given a convincing argument, but because I’m a person with a disability making claims about disability, and it just feels <em>uncomfortable </em>to voice hard objections&#8230; I get this&#8230; But for my work, it is<em> poison</em>.&#8221;<span id="more-54279"></span></p>
<p><a href="https://elizabethbarnesphilosophy.weebly.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Elizabeth Barnes</a> is professor of philosophy at the University of Virginia. She is the author of <em><a href="https://global.oup.com/academic/product/health-problems-9780192883476" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Health Problems: Philosophical Puzzles about the Nature of Health</a> </em>(2023) and <a href="https://academic.oup.com/book/8343" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Minority Body: A Theory of Disability</em></a> (2016), among other works, which you can learn about at <a href="https://elizabethbarnesphilosophy.weebly.com/papers.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">her website</a> and at <a href="https://philpeople.org/profiles/elizabeth-barnes-2" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PhilPapers</a>.</p>
<p>In the following guest post, she shares her personal reflections about disagreement, focusing on what she has learned from her interactions with someone with whom she has disagreed quite strongly over the years on a matter of great importance to her.</p>
<p>This is the sixth entry in the <a class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://dailynous.com/tag/summer-guest-post-series-2025/">2025 Summer Guest Post Series</a>. (It will stay pinned to the top of the home page for a few days.)</p>
